        "### Part 3 - Analysis & Critical Thinking\n",
        "My implementation uses fixed thresholds for hemoglobin, white blood cell count, platelets, and creatinine, then labels a patient as high risk if they have a critical hemoglobin value, multiple abnormal labs, or chemotherapy combined with cytopenia or renal dysfunction. One failure mode is that this logic may over-flag patients whose abnormalities are chronic or expected. For example, a patient with long-standing anemia from a non-oncology cause could still trigger a “high-risk” label even if the current visit is clinically stable. A second failure mode is under-classification: I used total WBC rather than absolute neutrophil count, so a patient with a normal total WBC but severe neutropenia would be missed.\n",
        "\n",
        "The notebook also omits several checks a real system should include. I do not evaluate potassium, sodium, liver function tests, temperature, performance status, allergies, treatment line, or recent hospitalization. I also do not interpret the free-text clinical note beyond storing it. In real oncology practice, symptoms such as fever, bleeding, dehydration, chest pain, or active infection could be more urgent than the lab pattern alone.\n",
